entry.content:
      &lt;div class=&#34;notice&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://twitter.com/kraminator&#34;&gt;Jonathon Kram&lt;/a&gt; has informed me that Kramdown does, indeed, support Footnotes. Using it is likely easier than the method I describe in this post. Thanks, Jonathon!&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;None of Jekyll&amp;rsquo;s Markdown renderers support footnotes out of the box&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:1&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:1&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;, but a &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/triplecanopy/redcarpet&#34;&gt;RedCarpet fork&lt;/a&gt; has the feature. Here&amp;rsquo;s how I got footnotes working in two easy steps:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-use-the-fork&#34;&gt;1) Use the fork&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The RedCarpet gem we want to use is not available on &lt;a href=&#34;https://rubygems.org&#34;&gt;RubyGems.org&lt;/a&gt;, but Bundler can install it directly from GitHub. Add a &lt;code&gt;Gemfile&lt;/code&gt; to your Jekyll site&amp;rsquo;s root directory that looks like this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-ruby&#34; data-lang=&#34;ruby&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;source &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;https://rubygems.org&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;gem &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;jekyll&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;gem &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;redcarpet&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;github&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;triplecanopy/redcarpet&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Run &lt;code&gt;bundle install&lt;/code&gt; and then you should be all ready to go.&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:2&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:2&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-configure-redcarpet&#34;&gt;2) Configure RedCarpet&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You have to configure Jekyll to use RedCarpet for Markdown rendering, but you also have to configure RedCarpet to use the &lt;code&gt;footnotes&lt;/code&gt; extension. Add these lines to your &lt;code&gt;_config.yml&lt;/code&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-ruby&#34; data-lang=&#34;ruby&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;markdown&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; redcarpet
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;redcarpet&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;  &lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;extensions&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;footnotes&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s it! You now have footnotes with Jekyll.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Enjoy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;footnotes&#34; role=&#34;doc-endnotes&#34;&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li id=&#34;fn:1&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Footnotes is not an official Markdown feature, but was added by &lt;a href=&#34;http://michelf.ca/projects/php-markdown/&#34;&gt;PHP-Markdown&lt;/a&gt; and a few derivative projects. The feature hasn&amp;rsquo;t made it in to RedCarpet proper (by way of &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/vmg/sundown&#34;&gt;Sundown&lt;/a&gt;) because of the concerted effort by GitHub, Reddit, etc. to develop and support a Markdown standard which will replace Sundown. See &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/vmg/sundown/pull/141#issuecomment-10846092&#34;&gt;this issue&lt;/a&gt; if you&amp;rsquo;re interested in learning more.&amp;#160;&lt;a href=&#34;#fnref:1&#34; class=&#34;footnote-backref&#34; role=&#34;doc-backlink&#34;&gt;&amp;#x21a9;&amp;#xfe0e;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li id=&#34;fn:2&#34;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will now have to use &lt;code&gt;bundle exec jekyll&lt;/code&gt; to invoke Bundler and pick up the correct RedCarpet gem. If that&amp;rsquo;s a pain, there are &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/mpapis/rubygems-bundler&#34;&gt;workarounds&lt;/a&gt; for &lt;code&gt;bundle exec&lt;/code&gt;.&amp;#160;&lt;a href=&#34;#fnref:2&#34; class=&#34;footnote-backref&#34; role=&#34;doc-backlink&#34;&gt;&amp;#x21a9;&amp;#xfe0e;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;We all know that naming things is one of &lt;a href=&#34;http://martinfowler.com/bliki/TwoHardThings.html&#34;&gt;the hard things&lt;/a&gt; in Computer Science. It turns out that this is also a problem in network/system administration. So many servers. So hard to come up with names for them all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Naming schemes help, but they are also difficult to come up with. Thankfully, &lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/&#34;&gt;there&amp;rsquo;s a wiki for that&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A few characteristics of a good machine name:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;One word, if possible — avoid the CamelCase v. under_score war&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Memorable — If you need to look it up, you picked a bad name&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Easy to spell — Help you help yourself&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Not embarrasing — I once named a server &amp;ldquo;Woody&amp;rdquo; (whoops)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Any naming scheme chosen must provide a multitude of names that fit the chriteria above. Some of my favorite schemes from this list:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Bible_Names&#34;&gt;Bible Names&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Big_Lebowski_Characters&#34;&gt;Big Lebowski Characters&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Shakespeare_Characters&#34;&gt;Shakespeare Characters&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Elements&#34;&gt;Elements&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Fraggle_Rock_Characters&#34;&gt;Fraggle Rock Characters&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/James_Bond_Villains&#34;&gt;James Bond Villans&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Mexican_Foods&#34;&gt;Mexican Foods&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Simpsons&#34;&gt;Simpsons&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://namingschemes.com/Wrestlers&#34;&gt;Wrestlers&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So far I&amp;rsquo;ve usually stuck to TV show characters because they are memorable and plentiful. Series I&amp;rsquo;ve used as naming schemes include &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_recurring_Cheers_characters&#34;&gt;Cheers&lt;/a&gt; (hence: Woody), &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M*A*S*H_(TV_series)#Characters&#34;&gt;M*A*S*H&lt;/a&gt;, and most recently &lt;a href=&#34;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arrested_Development_Characters&#34;&gt;Arrested Development&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://jerodsanto.net/drop/arrested_development_gob_magic-20120322-164935.png&#34; alt=&#34;Gob the Illusionist&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Come on, who wouldn&amp;rsquo;t want a server names after that guy?!&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;Picking up a new framework can be a daunting task, especially if you&amp;rsquo;re simultaneously learning a new language. I&amp;rsquo;ve done this before when I learned Ruby &amp;amp; Rails all in one fell swoop. It was not easy. I&amp;rsquo;m doing it again with Objective-J and &lt;a href=&#34;http://cappuccino.org&#34;&gt;Cappuccino&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Along the way I&amp;rsquo;ve compiled a list of valuable resources. I believe many others will be taking this same journey in the coming days (especially once &lt;a href=&#34;http://280atlas.com&#34;&gt;Atlas&lt;/a&gt; drops), so I&amp;rsquo;m sharing my findings for the benefit of all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;laying-foundation&#34;&gt;Laying Foundation&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0596517742?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;tag=standadeviat-20&amp;amp;linkCode=as2&amp;amp;camp=1789&amp;amp;creative=390957&amp;amp;creativeASIN=0596517742&#34;&gt;JavaScript: The Good Parts&lt;/a&gt; - &lt;em&gt;the&lt;/em&gt; book to read on JavaScript&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0321503619?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;tag=standadeviat-20&amp;amp;linkCode=as2&amp;amp;camp=1789&amp;amp;creative=390957&amp;amp;creativeASIN=0321503619&#34;&gt;Cocoa Programming for Mac OS X&lt;/a&gt; - focus on the &amp;ldquo;how&amp;rdquo; of Cocoa&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0321535022?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;tag=standadeviat-20&amp;amp;linkCode=as2&amp;amp;camp=1789&amp;amp;creative=390957&amp;amp;creativeASIN=0321535022&#34;&gt;Cocoa Design Patterns&lt;/a&gt; - focus on the &amp;ldquo;why&amp;rdquo; of Cocoa&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://cappuccino.org/learn/&#34;&gt;Introduction to Cappuccino &amp;amp; Objective-J&lt;/a&gt; - you&amp;rsquo;ve probably already read this&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://cappuccino.org/learn/tutorials/objective-j-tutorial.php&#34;&gt;Learning Objective-J&lt;/a&gt; - this too, but if you haven&amp;rsquo;t you absolutely should&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://peepcode.com/products/objective-c-for-rubyists&#34;&gt;Objective-C for Rubyists&lt;/a&gt; - great ($9) screencast if you&amp;rsquo;re coming from a Ruby background like me&lt;/p&gt;
